270","1250–1298":"1250–1298","1255–Male":"1255–Deceased","1276–Female":"1276–Deceased","1195–1238":"1195–1238","1195–1268":"1195–1268","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1195":"1195","1283":"1283","1270":"1270","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1268":"1268","1235":"1235","1255":"1255","1244":"1244","1276":"1276","1298":"1298","Sockburn, Durham, England":"Sockburn, Durham, England","Durham, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Durham, Durham, England, United Kingdom","Durham, Durham, England":"Durham, Durham, England","Sockburn, Darlington, England":"Sockburn, Durham, England, United Kingdom","Sockeburne, Durham, England":"Sockburn, Durham, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Conyers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire, of Norman origin): habitational name from either of two places in northern France, Coignières in Seine-et-Oise or Cogners in Sarthe. Alternatively, a variant of   Conyer  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Conyer","meanings":["English: occupational name for a minter, a coiner of money, from an agent derivative of Old French <i>coignier</i> ‘to stamp money, to mint’."]}]},{"name":"Humphrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Humphry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfrey","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":34,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Humphrey Conyers Lord Sockburn was born in 1225, in Sockburn, Durham, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Knight John Conyers, was 30 and his mother, Lady Alice Manning - Lady Conyers, was 30. He died in 1270, in Durham, Durham, England, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1225–1270":"1225–1270","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1230–1283":"1230–1283","1244–1270":"1244–1270","1250–1298":"1250–1298","1255–Male":"1255–Surnud","1276–Female":"1276–Surnud","1195–1238":"1195–1238","1195–1268":"1195–1268","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1195":"1195","1283":"1283","1270":"1270","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1268":"1268","1235":"1235","1255":"1255","1244":"1244","1276":"1276","1298":"1298","Sockburn, Durham, England":"Sockburn, Durham, England","Durham, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Durham, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Durham, Durham, England":"Durham, Durham, England","Sockburn, Darlington, England":"Sockburn, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sockeburne, Durham, England":"Sockburn, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1225–1270":"1225–1270","12